Hyperbolic billiards of pure  supergravities  



Marc Henneaux
and
Bernard Julia 


 Physique Theorique et Mathematique,
Universite Libre
de Bruxelles, C.P. 231, B-1050, Bruxelles, Belgium 

  Centro de Estudios Cientificos, Casilla
1469, Valdivia, Chile 


 Laboratoire de Physique Theorique de l'Ecole Normale
Superieure, 
 24, rue Lhomond, F-75231 Paris CEDEX 05, France 






 
We compute the billiards that emerge in the
Belinskii-Khalatnikov-Lifshitz (BKL) limit for all pure
supergravities in  spacetime dimensions, as well as for
,  supergravities coupled to  () Maxwell
supermultiplets. We find that just as for the cases  and
 investigated previously, these billiards can be identified
with the fundamental Weyl chambers of hyperbolic Kac-Moody
algebras. Hence, the dynamics is chaotic in the BKL limit. A new
feature arises, however, which is that the relevant Kac-Moody
algebra can be the Lorentzian extension of a twisted  affine
Kac-Moody algebra, while the  and  cases are untwisted.
This occurs for , where one gets , and for
 and , for which one gets . An
understanding of this property is provided by showing that the
data relevant for determining the billiards are the restricted root system  and the maximal split subalgebra  of
the finite-dimensional real symmetry algebra characterizing the
toroidal reduction to  spacetime dimensions. To summarise:
split symmetry controls chaos.





Introduction 
  As it has been shown recently, the classical
dynamics of the spatial scale factors and of the dilaton(s) (if
any) of -dimensional gravity coupled to -forms and scalar
fields can be described, in the vicinity of a spacelike
singularity, as a billiard motion in a region of hyperbolic space
bounded by hyperplanes(As it has become
standard practice in the field, the word billiard  used as a
noun in the singular denotes the dynamical system consisting of a
ball moving freely on a "table" (region in some Riemannian
space), with elastic bounces against the edges. Billiard 
also sometimes means the table itself.) . This generalizes known
results for pure gravity in  spacetime dimensions
. Furthermore, in the case of the bosonic
sector of -dimensional supergravity or -dimensional
supergravities, the relevant billiard turns out to be identifiable
with the fundamental Weyl chamber of the Kac-Moody algebras
,  or  - which are
respectively the overextensions of , 
and , i.e., , 
 and 
 -, while for -dimensional pure gravity, the algebra
is the overextension  of 
. The geometrical reflexions occurring when the system
hits the billiard walls are fundamental Weyl reflexions and the
motion can thus be identified with an (infinite) Weyl word. The
fact that the underlying Kac-Moody algebras are hyperbolic
(provided  for pure gravity) explains the
chaotic behaviour of these systems as one approaches the
singularity.

When reduced to four spacetime dimensions, the above models
correspond to pure  supergravity, or to  supergravity
coupled to a collection of  Maxwell/Yang-Mills multiplets
( Maxwell multiplets for pure ,  supergravity,
 vector multiplets for ,  supergravity with 
 or  Yang-Mills field). Only the  case
defines a pure supergravity theory in four spacetime dimensions.
The purpose of this article is to investigate systematically the
billiards that describe the dynamics of all pure 
supergravities () in the vicinity of a spacelike
singularity. We also investigate  supergravity coupled
to a collection of an arbitrary number  of  vector
multiplets.

We find that the billiards for all these models can also be
associated with hyperbolic Kac-Moody algebras. Furthermore, we
prove that "split symmetry controls chaos" in the following
sense: let  be the finite-dimensional real U-duality
algebra that appears in the toroidal compactification of the
theory to 3 dimensions. Then, the hyperbolic Kac-Moody algebra
whose fundamental Weyl chamber determines the billiard is the
overextension of the "maximal split subalgebra"  of
 (and not of  itself except when 
 and  coincide, which occurs only when 
is split, i.e., maximally non-compact). This explains in
particular why it is  (rather
than the overextension of the split form  of
the non-split ) that
determines the heterotic billiard.
However, while the Kac-Moody
algebras of the previously studied models are given by standard
overextensions of finite-dimensional Lie algebras, some of the
theories investigated here are characterized by a new feature: the
extension involves a "twist". Specifically, the twist occurs for
 and , for which one gets respectively the Lorentzian
extensions  and  of the twisted
affine algebras  and  with Dynkin diagrams

 

Note that the role of  versus  was understood
in the context of non-split -duality for the -models
in.  In that precise case, there is no twist.

In the next section, we set up our conventions and terminology.
Then, we derive the central theorem that relates the Kac-Moody
algebra  whose fundamental Weyl chamber is the billiard
table to the maximal split subalgebra  and the restricted  root system of the real  symmetry algebra 
 appearing in 3 spacetime dimensions (section
). We show quite generally that  is
the overextension of , with a twist only when the root
system is of -type. The theorem covers all pure supergravity
models in  spacetime dimensions, as well as  SUGRA
with  Maxwell multiplets. So when the U-duality algebra 
 is not split (i.e. not maximally non-compact) its maximal
split subalgebra , which controls chaos, is smaller. The
analysis also explains the wall multiplicities. In section
, the billiard is computed in the particular case of
 supergravity directly in  dimensions, without going to
 dimensions. This sheds a different light on the twist.
Finally, we relate the occurrence of the twist to a property of
real forms of untwisted but non split affine Kac-Moody algebras
.

Conventions 
 
Let  be a complex, finite-dimensional Lie algebra
and let  be one of its real forms. We denote by 
 the corresponding untwisted algebra of currents
(where all the currents are integer-moded). It is a real form of
the untwisted affine extension of , defined from
the Chevalley-Serre presentation by adding generators associated
with the new, "affine" root , where 
is the highest root of  and  the null root of
 (see; 
 is  in Kac's notations).
We shall also consider real twisted affine algebras, but only in
their split form. These are again defined from the standard Dynkin
diagrams in terms of Chevalley-Serre generators and relations, but
one considers only real combinations. We adopt Kac's notations
 in the twisted case. Given a split (untwisted or
twisted) affine Kac-Moody algebra , we define its real
Lorentzian extension  by adding an
"overextended root" to its Dynkin diagram and
considering the corresponding set of generators and relations over
the reals. The overextended root is attached to the affine root
 with a single line in the untwisted case. For the
twisted algebras  - the only twisted cases we
shall encounter here -, the overextended root is attached to the
unique root carrying label , which is the longest root. Note
that this longest root is not  the root  of
.  More information on overextensions is given in the
appendix.

To characterize the real form , we adopt the Tits-Sakate
theory as developed for instance in. One selects a
maximally non-compact Cartan subalgebra of  and one
diagonalizes simultaneously in  all the operators 
with  in this Cartan subalgebra. This defines the restricted
roots and the restricted root system , which can be either
one of the standard reduced root systems , , ,
, , , ,  or , or one of the nonreduced
 systems. The  root system is obtained by merging the
 and  root systems in such a way that the long roots of
 are the short roots of . It is called nonreduced
because  and  can be simultaneously roots (if  is a
short root of ,  is a long root of ). The
restricted roots include all the standard roots of a Lie
algebra, which we call the "maximal split subalgebra" following Borel
and Tits and denote
by . Note, however, that there are in general
crucial differences between the restricted root
system of  and the standard root system of  :
(i) twice a root of  can be a restricted root
and (ii) the restricted roots can come with a non trivial
multiplicity. The dimension of the maximally non-compact Cartan
subalgebra of , which is the Cartan subalgebra of 
, is called the real rank of  and denoted by . It
is only if  is the split real form of 
that  coincides with . This information is
encoded in the Tits-Sakate diagrams and given for
instance in (table VI, chapter X). The importance of
non split real forms of U-duality groups dates back to supergravity days
. The facts that its precise real form is related to the
 compactification symmetry and that this fixes the maximal
oxidation possible have also been used and exposed repeatedly.




A general theorem 
  
When reduced to  spacetime dimensions, the bosonic sectors of
all  pure supergravity theories become the Einstein theory
coupled to a coset model  where  is the maximal compact
subgroup of , and where  depends on . We give
in the first column of table I of the concluding section the
(real) Lie algebra 
of the  symmetry group . The
information is taken from.

Now, the computation of the billiard can be carried out in any
number of dimensions  because the dominant walls that
define the billiard are invariant under toroidal dimensional
reduction and dualization. If the theory is
explicitly known in  dimensions, which is the case here, the
easiest way to uncover the underlying Kac-Moody structure is to
analyze the billiard in that dimension, where it is particularly
transparent. In this section, we determine the billiard for
general coset models coupled to gravity in  dimensions, where
 is not necessarily the split real form of 
. Our theorem will be a generalization to the non-split
case of the results obtained in for the split case,
where the Lagrangians of of maximally non-compact
coset models were investigated.

