Twisted case - link with real forms of affine algebras 
 
As we have seen, adding the last overextended root is direct and
involves no subtlety. The twist arises already - and only - at
the level of the affinization. With this in mind, the appearance
of twisted algebras in the description of the billiard is not
surprizing if one recalls the theory of real forms of affine
Kac-Moody algebras. For the "almost split" case their
classification is given in. By mere inspection of the
tables given in that paper, it can be observed that if 
is the maximal split subalgebra of the finite-dimensional real Lie
algebra , the affine extension  may not be the maximal split subalgebra of  . In
particular, the maximal split subalgebra of the current algebras
 and  is , while the
maximal split subalgebra of the current algebra 
 is . Note that for both  and
, twice the shortest simple root is a root, a feature
that the authors of denote by adding a  over
the short root on the restricted Dynkin diagram.

On the other hand, the maximal split subalgebras of the other
current algebras relevant to the supergravity models under
consideration, namely, ,  (with 
), ,  (with ),
 and  involve no
twist and are respectively , ,
, ,  and 
.

Conclusions and summary 
 
In this paper, we have established a theorem that enables one to
derive the billiard dynamics of all  pure supergravity models
directly from their  formulation: the relevant data that
control the dynamics in the vicinity of a spacelike singularity
are the restricted root system and the maximal split subalgebra of
the real  symmetry algebra. The precise rule is: the
Kac-Moody algebra  relevant for the billiard motion is
just the overextension of the maximal split subalgebra ,
, except when the restricted
root system is of -type, in which case there is a twist.
Because the Kac-Moody algebras that emerge for the models are all
hyperbolic, the dynamics is asymptotically chaotic.

Our theorem goes beyond  pure supergravities and covers all
systems whose reduction to  is a non-linear sigma model 
coupled to gravity. This is the case for  supergravities
with  vector ("Maxwell") multiplets, for which the 
symmetry algebra is . It is also the case, for
instance, for the   exceptional Einstein-Maxwell
theories of. Since these latter models are
described in  by the real Lie algebras , 
,  or  (corresponding to
the real, complex, quaternionic or octonionic Jordan algebras,
respectively), one can immediately infer that their
billiard is the fundamental Weyl chamber of the hyperbolic
Kac-Moody algebra . Indeed,  is in all
cases the maximal split subalgebra (and the restricted root system
is of  type).

Our results are summarized in the following table, in which we
give the number of supersymmetries (), the real symmetry
algebra that emerges in  dimensions (), the
corresponding restricted root system (), the maximal
split subalgebra () and the hyperbolic Kac-Moody algebra
that controls the BKL limit (). In the last three lines,
 is the number of coupled Maxwell multiplets (thus the fourth
line corresponds to ). We denote the root systems by small
letters to distinguish them from the Lie algebras.




















